metadata.name: Modular Permutation  #44
metadata.description:
The permutation of sounds and colors tries to understand the natural order of numbers and their forms represented in nature, silence is where that number meets infinity, noise is the movement of air, silence flows like this the chaos of numbers, creating the abstract . this abstract simulation is part of a cultural context and a digital effervescence, where computers are no longer tools and become co-authors in the random factor that simulates chaos in this modular composition, both in image and in sound.

by Marcelo Moura · Brazil, 2022 | GTK:javascript/hydra'ojack Music: vcvrack

metadata.name: Glitch3D SOUND Mutations #18
metadata.description:
In the vastness of the cosmos there are beings so sensitive to waves that they move as the universe sounds. And you just need to look at things from a different angle to understand the Whole and the Minimum.

The 3D shapes animation is coordinated and responsive to the music played in the environment (there are 3 possible soundtracks).
This piece intends to create different impressions of the generated shape depending on the viewer's position. This is possible using the mouse Scroll up or down. You can explore as much as you like.

Each generated part will belong to one of the Nine GenoME's. Its 3D parameters are dependent on the fxrand() function. This is done to add a simulation of genetic variability, however similarities will always exist in the same GenoMe.

This work is a collaboration between @nt_worm and @nax_of_malpas.

(Click on the Screen to start the Soundtrack)
(MouseScroll to explore different positions)
(On Windowed mode use Shift + MouseScroll to move arround the enviroment)

metadata.name: Dencity #313
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Force projection (Compound 230205) #12
metadata.description:
Structures of unknown origin, purpose unclear
One of a series of 128 generative geometry generators by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut

keyboard:
'a' : toggle auto renew, off -> 60s -> 30s -> 10s
'r' : toggle auto rotate
'n' : new iteration with the same features

mouse:
top left corner: toggle auto renew, off -> 60s -> 30s -> 10s
top right corner: toggle auto rotate
bottom left corner: new iteration with the same features

Bottom right corner show status of auto refresh: hex=60s, triangle=30s, circle=10s

WebGL piece using three.js, mainly targeting desktop exploration. Performance may vary depending on platform, check before minting.

metadata.name: Assemblage #34
metadata.description:
Assemblage:
  - a collection or gathering of things or people
  - a machine or object made of pieces fitted together
  - a work of art made by grouping together found or unrelated objects

More than often, it is the case that my projects start out as collections of unrelated ideas. These ideas sometimes revolve around specific algorithmic concepts, with the aim to combine, remix and chain together methods in some novel way. In other instances these ideas are a vague vision of particular aesthetic that I'm trying to chase down. Usually though, it's a bit of a mix of both. Assemblage was conceived in this manner, evolving from the combination of several Genuary sketches.

To play into this narrative and further it a little bit, while searching for a suitable name for the project, I thought that the art in of itself, in some way, looked like a disassembled or shattered machine, with the constituent pieces scattered and strewn around in a chaotic manner. This is in contrast to fact that the items are actually positioned in a very orderly and systematic manner, where no two shapes can technically overlap or intersect, creating an interplay of Order and Chaos.

Press S to download a PNG version of the artwork. 2400 x 3000 pixels.
It can take up to a couple of seconds to generate all of the graphics.

metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #209
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: CityScape: Istanbul #52
metadata.description:
Istanbul is a city that straddles the Bosporus Strait, and lies in both Europe and Asia, with a population of over 15 million residents. Most of the population is located in big iconic hills known as the "Seven Hills of Istanbul". 

   In this project, I tried to capture and interpret the daily life routine of the people who live in these hills with the viewing point from Bosphorus. There are three camera angle possibilities to examine the details in different layers. Also, building types, the slope of the hill, and green area density vary in between those scenarios. There are two time zones: day and night. In the night scene, there is a possibility to obtain the crescent moon which is the symbol of the culture inhabits in these lands.

To save as a high-quality image, open in live view and click yes on the incoming prompt.

Created with p5js
